Note that, in **Chart 1**, in addition to the species, the **first hominids** and **humans** are highlighted. These are not the only classifications used to understand our evolution, which is why we decided to explain them to avoid confusion (<htcite0>):
- **Hominids**: This is the broadest group. In addition to including us and other extinct hominin species, it also includes great apes, such as gorillas and chimpanzees;
- **Hominins**: Encompass all human groups (genus *Homo*), in addition to *Australopithecus*, *Paranthropus*, and *Ardipithecus*;
- **Humans**: Are all extinct and existing species that belong to the genus *Homo*, excluding *Australopithecus*, *Paranthropus*, and *Ardipithecus*.

history.text:
Finally, the time has come to talk about us, *Homo sapiens*. However, before we begin this study, some points related to other species and to us must be highlighted:
- Our species is the eleventh species of the genus *Homo* that we will study;
- As shown in *Graph 2* and throughout the text, our species did not appear on planet Earth at the same time as the others;
- As can be seen in various figures on this page, the body structure of the species of the genus *Homo* is similar, as a result of shared DNA among us and, as seen, with other species, such as chimpanzees (*Pan troglodytes*) (<htcite0>);
- The fact that DNA is shared with other species can be confirmed when DNA can be extracted from fossils of species that went extinct recently (<htcite1>). When it is no longer possible to extract it, we can still compare the final result, which are the fossils;
- The understanding of DNA occurred only in the 20th century (<htcite2>), according to the Gregorian calendar. This did not prevent people like Charles Darwin (<htcite3>; <htcite4>; <htcite5>) from proposing beforehand what DNA later confirmed;
- Regarding the evolution of the knowledge and beliefs that characterize us, an observation must be made about the indigenous peoples of Mesoamerica (*Abya Yala*). Although we cannot refer to them as users of the scientific method, we must highlight that they were able to see the relationship between us and other monkeys within their worldview (<htcite6>; <htcite7>).
- Finally, regardless of the specific characteristics of the 11 species of the genus *Homo*, millions of years ago we separated from other species—in a process of speciation. This process continued thanks to genetic mutations. And we, *Homo sapiens*, who occupy the entire planet today, have our origins in Africa (<htcite8>).

Our human species, *Homo sapiens*, has other names that were given as we advanced our knowledge (<htcite0>; <htcite1>):
- *Homo sapiens sapiens*: this name appears in the comparisons we make between our species and other species. It is a name given by those who consider that *Homo sapiens* would actually be a larger group—a group that could even encompass Neanderthals, who would then be called *Homo sapiens neanderthalensis*;
- **Arcaíco**: term used to refer to our ancestors who lived in Africa between <htdate0> and <htdate1>;
- **Cro-Magnon**: term used for humans who lived in Europe between <htdate2> and <htdate3>.
